As I said on day one, all we have to do today is meet ourselves here.
Just as I have been changing things up a little each day to carry us to the next, on day thirty, we will continue to turn things on their side once again.‚Ä®Yoga is a discipline, a training for a meaningful life.¬†
An opportunity to know and understand your self.
Today you are going to choose your moves.¬†
Choose your quality of breath¬†
without my vocal guidance,¬†
but with my undying ever present and unshakable support.
We have come a long way.
I am not going to downplay it‚Ä¶
This is a big and beautiful deal.
Meet yourself here. Day 30.
Allow yourself to be moved.‚Ä®Trust me. You have everything you need.

I began this challenge fairly late. I only started at the end of January, and I honestly felt quite strange to just follow this with such delay. However, I have been wanting to start doing yoga for a while now, and it finally seemed like the right time for me. 
Generally, I have been very self-conscious about my level of fitness and my ability to do physical exercise for probably eight years now (currently I'm 21). Although I have tried lots of different types of sport over the years, nothing really stuck, and nothing was able to make me feel good for a longer period of time. 
With yoga, I hoped that it would be different. That it could be something I can do just because it made me feel good. Without pressuring myself to excellent at it, without doing it to become skinnier, without doing it with any other motivation than to be kind to myself. Kind to my body, my heart, and my mind. And honestly, it did not work like that every single day. Sometimes I lacked motivation, sometimes I really was not mentally able to challenge myself the way I wished I would have. But that's okay. Because I have showed up every single day, for 30 days in a row. And even after the practices where I did not feel able to give it my all, I still felt good about myself for doing it. My body has been feeling better than it has for a long, long time, and my mind has become a lot more peaceful. And I am just incredibly happy and proud to have followed this practice.
So, thank very much for everything, Adriene

I needed a few days to collect my thoughts and express my deep feelings about this month as well as about the last day of practice in January. Last year I participated on the ‚Äúbreath‚Äù journey and I still vividly remember the whole month of me practicing. I remember skipping days, trying to get it over with and I remember the last day, when I got annoyed and irritated at not knowing which pose you were doing and failing to do the flow in sync with you. A lot has changed this year, as I set myself the intention of doing yoga every day for 365 days. This whole month I surprised myself every day by showing up regularly and turning this yoga ritual into a daily act of love towards myself. As an empath and a person that has been struggling with setting up boundaries and protecting my own peace, yoga has brought me to a place of patience and has created a new space for me, in which i get to protect myself from energy that isn‚Äôt mine and tune into my own pure energy that is within me and move with it throughout my day. Day 30 was very beautiful and emotional for me. I‚Äôve never been the type that lets out emotions easily, but with this practice I felt my emotions all over the place. I felt gratitude towards myself for creating my own ‚Äúlove cave‚Äù with candles, crystals and incence and gratitude towards adriene for sharing her wisdom and her presence with me. This time I knew I could trust my intuition and move in ways that felt good and connecting with her movements later and knowing that it was all okay. It is truly mesmerizing watching you move with such grace and beauty and I am honored to be able to call you my teacher, Adriene. Sending lots of love from Austria.

It took me a couple of extra days to come up with enough courage to practice on "Day 30" knowing I wouldn't get cued (even after years of practicing yoga on and off with in person classes and online). Thank you so much Adriene for guiding us on this journey. I have a technical suggestion for the videos, if I may. And I hope I can explain it. So... When I join the routine, I place my mat parallel to yours, I think many are doing the same. So when sitting, you face us and we face you. Like standing in front of a mirror. And when you turn right and get on all four, we turn left and get on all four. From then on, until we sit and face each other again, your top of the mat is your right and our top of the mat is our left. When you start doing the poses, sometimes your first side is the camera side, and since we mirror you, our first side is then facing the opposite wall where we don't see you but hear you. Nothing wrong with that, just that I need to turn my head and peek quite often. And when it's time for your second side, where you face your window, this is when we can face your way and do the pose by actually seeing you. It's not always the case, sometimes you begin facing the window. But here is my suggestion. Especially when we try a new pose, if you start with your second side, that is, doing the pose looking at the window, it will then be time for us to do the first side facing you. So we get to see where the motion is going without turning our heads and peek. And then when it is your second side, you then look at the camera, and this time, although we look at our back walls, we now know what to do as we just completed the first side by looking at you. It is just a switch of your sides, and we can start the poses by looking at your way and learning them. I may sound silly, but that's what I thought in those peeking moments all along the way. Thank you once again, for touching our lives. Namaste!

Thank you so much for these 30 days and beyond, Adriene and team! One big thing I learned from MOVE was that balancing poses get me out of my thinking mind and into my body and breath like no others. With balancing poses it is such a delightful challenge and I find myself noticing my muscles, how I stabilize when I find strength in my core or activated that inner thigh. Today I was quite surprised as to what we were doing. I remember seeing a comment on one of the videos a couple days ago saying that us "newbies" would not see this coming, and I sure didn't! That being said, I was truly amazed with how I did! I still struggle with how far I've come with this. Day 1 of Move randomly popped up on my yt feed when I needed it most. I was depressed, hating myself, and wondering what I could do to feel better both physically and mentally. I was also born with severely clubbed feet (meaning they turn in quite a bit) and even though I had surgery, I was lazy at the time and chose not to do the therapy exercises, and as a result, regressed tremendously. This has helped me get flexibility in my ankles that I never had before! That being said, from the bottom of my heart, thank you so much, to Adriene, to Benji, and to everyone else who has taken this journey. This is just the beginning! You are strong, and you are worthy! I have been coming to the mat with this community to start off the new year for the past 5 years. The last day is always filled with an overwhelming mixture of accomplishment and deep love and acceptance for myself and others. This year I reflected on how much I've changed since last year and how loss creates space for unexpected gifts.¬†

During last year's practice, I was coming out of a particularly bad episode of depression and focused on regrowing my sense of self-love and promoting healing. This year, I am mentally stronger but struggled physically as I came down with COVID on the 3rd day of practice. I still managed to come to the mat everyday, with some modifications and patience with myself.¬†

This year was particularly special for me as it was the first time I trusted myself to listen to my mind and body and "find what feels good," instead of sneaking peeks at the video to follow along with Adriene. Today I am grateful for change and growth. For self-love and self-trust. For beautiful moments with friends and family. And I am grateful to Adriene and Benji for providing this supportive community to allow us all the space to be our best authentic selves. Namaste, to Adriene and to every single one of you beautiful humans for showing up!

This practice and this community has been instrumental to this wonderful transformation of love. It is not always easy. It is quite difficult at times, to make the active choice to turn to discipline and mindfulness, even knowing the joy it will result in. But I remind myself of an affirmation I thought of, one that I would like to share with you.

"Happiness can be found in attending each present moment with mindfullness and openheartedness. This is a task one must tend their entire life to - however, it is the process, not the destination, that bears fruit to our existence."

Congratulations to all for completing this wonderful journey. May it mark the start of a lifelong process of love.

(this is gonna be long, but it turns out I have a lot to say haha)

Adriene, 
I've been doing yoga with you off and on since college. I say off and on because there were some months when I could hardly get myself out of bed, let alone to the mat. I remember at the end of 2017, when I was getting ready for my first semester of grad school and you were getting ready for True. I had just finished the new beginnings video, thinking to myself "huh. I could do that." I gave it a go but couldn't get myself to stick with it daily, so I gave up; what's the point if I won't make it every day? What can I get out of it if I'm not doing it right? So I cycled through your other videos and left True on the back burner.

Then it's the end of 2018, and you announce Dedicate. I'm in a better place mentally since getting on medication, and I think to myself "this is my chance! I'll get it right this time!" So I set my alarm, because at that point morning practices before work suited me best, and got on the mat. I was more consistent this time, but I still couldn't quite make it through. Disappointed in myself, I once again set it aside and cycled through your other videos.

Fast forward to the end of 2019. I'm looking forward to 2020 and to Home, just like everyone else -- it's gonna be my last year of grad school, and even though school is my main stressor, I'm excited to write my thesis. I'd also gotten a new job at that point, and spent the first two months convinced I was going to get fired before getting moved to a new department. I had a mostly stable routine and thought I'd finally get through it this year (spoiler alert: I didn't). I got further along than previous years, but still not on time.

March 2020 didn't really change much for me; I was an essential worker and my classes were already online, so I carried on as normal. But I went back to Home with a new sense of determination. Even if I didn't do it every day, I was damn well going to finish it out.

And I did! It took longer than 30 days, but I did it. I felt "at home" in my body and was inspired and decided to work backwards -- I would tackle Dedicate next, and then go back to True. By July I hadn't quite finished, but I wanted to give Revolution a try, so I set my sights on that 31 day yoga journey and left the rest of True (and uncovering my "true self") for August.

From there I hopped around the playlist of yoga sequences I'd made from my favorite of your and Sarah Beth Yoga's videos. I still struggled a lot with consistency, but I knew that yoga made me feel good, and at that point it had become a keystone habit for me. (Also, I'd apparently lost 30 pounds -- who knew! My sister teases me for "stretching" as a workout, but I sure showed her!)

Then Breath came along last year, and even though I was annoyed that it wasn't called Breathe, I was still committed to seeing it through. I was kinder to myself this time around; I knew that even if I didn't get through it live, I would still finish it out. And in February, I did. Another March came around, and I decided to work backwards like I had before: Home, Dedicate, True, and Revolution, straight through. I mixed in other videos, tried new routines each week to keep myself going, but I could feel myself slipping; I was gaining weight again, I didn't like the way I felt in my body, I was regressing in my mental health. But I recommitted -- got myself into a new routine of yoga after work, followed along as best I could with your playlists for the remaining months of the year. 

And then came Move.

What did I want to move closer to? Much like with Home and True, I chose myself. I wanted to like myself -- not even love, because I knew that that was a long shot, but I could at least do that.
I checked the calendar (mostly 20 to 30 minute videos, totally doable!) signed up for the emails, and got ready.

And today, January 31st 2022, I completed the journey along with you.

I've read comments from people who cried doing your videos, and while I've definitely teared up, today was the first day that those tears actually fell. I had felt myself getting stronger with each practice, and today I was going to prove it and honor that strength.

I came up with a little prayer/mantra to whisper to myself throughout today's practice, one that you helped me to find the words for: "I am grateful for my body, for it has carried me through these 30 days. I love my body, for it has carried me through these 30 days. I choose my body, for it has carried me through these 30 days. I am my body; I have carried through these 30 days." Sat for the first few minutes of practice crying and repeating that to myself, and then I dove in and did my own thing. A couple times I looked up and you were doing the same thing, which warmed my heart. I wasn't alone; I had you.

I finished today with my mantra, and I will try to start each day moving forward with it, too. That's my word of the year, "try" -- to do better, to be kinder. I tried this month with Move, and I'm very proud to say that I've succeeded. I'm so full right now that it's taken me over an hour to get all these words out, but I did it. I did it.

Thank you.

Yesterday something terrible happened that left me unstable in lots of mental pain.  I mean,  im still in relatively good health, nobody died, and i still have a home, so i guess it is not that bad.  But this event was unjust, unpedictable and sent me spiraling to a very sinister place. Today i woke up feeling no difference. Everything was awful. Finally when i got into bed i reached for my gratitude journal, deciding i will write that i'm thankful for food, sunrays falling through the window and my bed - you know,  stuff to be thankful for on one of those Bad Days. But then i realised: i didn't do my yoga today! Every day i write that im thankful for my "n"th day of yoga, which gives me small dopamine hits whenever i see my progress. Well, if i'm on over 50 days long streak of daily yoga practice, i can't fail today, even if i feel like shit and existing feels like punishment. So on 02:39AM i got on the mat and started stretching. I must admit i was mostly observing and following Adriene, because in my current state deciding what feels good was almost impossible. Though I made some minor adjustments, hip stretches instead of downward dogs etc. 

I feel much better know. I'm thankful that i did not fail, that i rolled out of my bed onto the floor, despite the very late hour to desperately do yoga in an attempt to change something and feel better. Im thankful for unstopable passage of time,  which may seem terrifying at first but is actually a blessing. It will pass. Nothing is eternal, everything is temporary. Everything will pass. I won't feel what i feel now, in some time. That's what i remind myself. 
I need to be up in 5 hours, and before that i need to fall asleep haha.

Im sending love to all people here. Thank you for this journey. Thank you Adriene for guiding us and being here.

Keeping myself accountable: Day 30!!!

At the start of the practice with the announcement of there not going to be any instruction, I panicked. But I quickly got into doing my own movements and following by breath, not long after I started getting lost, not naturally moving and seeking out instruction... I pushed on trying to get back into the flow and eventually I did. This somewhat represents my journey throught the whole practice. I was scared of failing yet again at the start, but then turning up became natural and fun thing only for it then to become difficult to find the time, energy or peace of mind to be fully emerged in the practice... Nearing the end of this challenge I again got into the fun and flow of showing up for practice. This is my third time trying the 30 day challenge, and third time lucky, I succeeded! I started the challenge with the goal of trying to see if i could keep myself accountable if i posted to the world whether i showed up, the fear of disappointing not just myself but others too was a great motivator but once I got into that end flow I realised I didnt need it anymore because I was truly capable of showing up and doing this for myself. 

I did it. I shed many tears throught the challenge at Adriene's kind words, especially the one about taking up space because we deserve to, but now I'm shedding tears because I am proud of being able to succeed in showing up for myself.

Thank you for this wonderful yoga challenge <3

Okay, so I started crying after literally 1 second of today's session. That's a new record, even for me, haha. 

This last year was tough. I had a burnout and was diagnosed with depression. I quit my old job and started therapy. I haven't moved much for most of 2021. I just didn't have the capacity. I decided to give it a try again. I had discovered YWA during that very first lockdown. But I was scared. Scared of "failing". And it was tough at first, getting back into movement. But I did. 30 consecutive days of yoga. I can't remember the last time I was so proud of myself.

I don't want to paint it prettier than it is. I'm still struggling. Therapy is hard. But I think I accomplished what I had promised myself to move towards on the very first day of this year's 30 days of yoga. I want to move (back) towards myself. Towards who I truly am. I managed to feel more in touch with myself again. To take better care of myself again. And this and even though it's just a milestone on what will still be a long journey, gives me hope. So much hope for the future. And that's incredible.

Last year on day 30 was the only day I missed out, because that very day the police knocked on my door to tell me, my brother had died in a car crash. He was innocent, on his way home from a new job, when a teenager, who had gotten his drivers license only 14 days earlier, engaged in an illegal car race with a friend, lost control and crashed into my brother on the opposite lane. The wreck didn't even look like a car anymore. Supposedly, my brother was dead right away. I hope, that's true.  
Ironically, my other brother had died in an almost identical way already in 1985. Also on his way back from work, when a transporter crashed into him frontally, killing him. 

Last year, after that event, I didn't catch up on day 30 anymore, and hardly did any yoga the rest of the year either, although I love this channel for several years now. These past few years have been so hard, not only because of the pandemic. I went through a traumatic and failed surgery myself (ending up with PTSD from it), had my best friend dump me, lost ALL other friends and social connections, too, had my chronic depression get so much worse, had my mother get diagnosed with cancer (she had surgery now but refused the chemo therapy, which worries me although I respect her decision), and most of the time now I'm too scared to even leave my apartment. 

But this January I "signed myself up" for this challenge again and didn't miss a day. Not even day 30 now, where I've got a candle for my brother burning. That might not sound like a big thing, but for me in my current state it is. And I hope to go back to the discipline I used to have before and just stick with daily yoga again now, because in the past that was always incredibly helpful not only physically but especially mentally. 
These past 30 days of practice felt like an embrace in some way. For that, I want to say a big thank you to Adriene, for the love, passion and work that goes into these videos and lessons. You have no idea how much you help people like me. Thank you! ‚ù§üß°üíõüíöüíôüíú

i wonder what i will be choosing. in the beginning of this journey, i wished for better health, contentedness, and success. that hasn't changed. yet you tickled my brain with this word, choose, it's so powerful. we make choices every single day, every minute. but how many of these choices are mindful? it's simple, but with mindfulness in the equation, meaning adds up to every choice. what is the meaning behind this choice, is it beneficial, to whom, etc.? and why is it important to make? ok look, with my existential crisis that has not even aged 24 hours, i'm pondering over my life, no regrets though. and i'm also thinking about the "choices" we choose not to make. everything is a choice, choosing to choose and choosing not to choose. it's just that some hold higher significance than others. like choosing myself and prioritizing my needs, which are always met, without fail, every time i step on the mat. i love this kind of thing. i think, after having thought of things, i choose to go easy on myself, and that going easy does not equate to being lazy or anything of the sort (lazy is good tho, sometimes). with that, i hope my percpective's widened a little bit more on how i choose to achieve my wishes.

Then it was surprise at my improved strength and flexibility, a sense of purpose to embody the Asana and marry the movement to my breath. Then a sense of humility and acceptance as I stumbled and fell off repeatedly from my balancing poses. Then at the end, an overwhelming sense of empowerment and confidence at having led the practice myself and meeting myself on the edge. A few tears shed at the end while saying Namaste to Adriene and this loving community with my gratitude.
I love you all. I love myself.
Let's meet again tomorrow on the mat. Namaste üôè

This journey was a bit different from what I expected on my part, I fell ill a week in and I'm still in pain in my back. I had to skip two days and then managed to recuperate when I was on heavier meds but since then I couldn't do my favourite poses (any back twist). I had to modify, accept the frustration that came in knowing that my body wasn't supporting me and realise that I'm still grateful for all the other muscles that got stronger. All the poses that I did for the first time and did them right and easily were the combination of years of daily practice, of moving my body within its limit, without going too far but still growing stronger and more confident in my skin. I hated sports and wasn't flexible, I hated my body but yoga really helped me shift all this perspective. Thank you Adriene for being an amazing teacher of yoga and of life. Namaste everybody.

Dear Adriene,
I would like to thank you for not only introducing me to yoga, which has become the greatest passion of mine and improved my health significantly, but for the most special and important gift there is - the gift of life.

You literally saved me in all possible ways. There was a time when your soft guiding voice was the only dear sound to my ears and the only link between my inner cage of hopeless and endless pain and the external world - you were my bridge of life, my breath. I was in a super dark place back then, and you not only gave me tools to face it and coupe with it, but showed me the light in people, in me and taught me how I can bring it into my world and even make it my reality of each and every moment.

Bless you and be sure your first class place in Heaven is waiting for you ;)

With love,
Sveta from Moscow, Russia

I can't express how grateful and happy I feel right now. I've been dealing with chronic panic, especially in my hips, for the last two years. Last year it got so bad that I had to stop the yoga journey on day 22. This January I luckily rediscovered how much good yoga does for my joints. Yes, it hurt sometimes. But I pushed through it and while that may sound stupid, I always felt less pain once I was done. I'm struggling a lot with my mental health and this journey gave me, like the years before, the opportunity to focus on finding what feels good. So... thank you. I'll definitely try to keep up this habit of working out with you once a day. It became my happy place, where I don't have to worry about my pain, ed, depression, whatever. I hope y'all had a great experience as well and that you enjoy day 30 as much as I do!
